# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] David Buckingham attended Barker College in Sydney.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He then obtained a Bachelor of Science and Master of Science, under Professor Raymond Le Fevre, from the University of Sydney and a PhD from the University of Cambridge supervised by John Pople.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was an 1851 Exhibition Senior Student in the Physical Chemistry Laboratory at the University of Oxford from 1955 to 1957, Lecturer and then Student (Fellow) at Christ Church, Oxford from 1955 to 1965 and University Lecturer in the Inorganic Chemistry Laboratory from 1958 to 1965.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was Professor of Theoretical Chemistry at the University of Bristol from 1965 to 1969.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was appointed Professor of Chemistry at the University of Cambridge in 1969.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in 1975, a Fellow of the American Physical Society in 1986 and a Foreign Associate of the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1992.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was a member of the International Academy of Quantum Molecular Science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] Buckingham was elected to the Australian Academy of Science in 2008 as a Corresponding Fellow.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was awarded the first Ahmed Zewail Prize in Molecular Sciences for pioneering contributions to the molecular sciences in 2006.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He won the Harrie Massey Medal and Prize in 1995.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He also played 10 first class cricket matches for Cambridge University and Free Foresters between 1955 and 1960, scoring 349 runs including two half-centuries at an average of 18.36.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He was President of Cambridge University Cricket Club between 1990 and 2009.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] Professor Buckingham finished his career as Emeritus Professor of Chemistry at the University of Cambridge, United Kingdom and Emeritus Fellow at Pembroke College, Cambridge.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] Professor Buckingham's research has focussed on the measurement and understanding of the electric, magnetic and optical properties of molecules; as well as on the theory of intermolecular forces.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] Initially he worked on dielectric properties of liquids, such as dipole moments of molecules in both solution and gas phases.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] He developed the theory of the interaction of molecules in liquids and gases with external electric and magnetic fields.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1959, he proposed a direct method of measurement of molecular quadrupole moments of molecules (measured in buckinghams), which he demonstrated experimentally in 1963 on the carbon dioxide molecule.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1960, he developed theories of solvent effects on nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectra and vibrational spectra of molecules.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1962 he considered the effect on NMR spectra of molecular orientation in a strong electric field, and developed a method to determine the absolute sign of the spin-spin coupling constant.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1968, he determined the first accurate values of hyperpolarizability using the Kerr effect.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1971 Buckingham and Laurence Barron pioneered the study of Raman optical activity, due to differences in the Raman scattering of left and right-polarized light by chiral molecules.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In the 1980s, he showed the importance of long-range intermolecular forces in determining the structure and properties of small molecule clusters, with particular applications in biological macromolecules.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1990 he predicted the linear effect of an electric field on the reflection of light at interfaces.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In 1995, he proved that the sum of the rotational strengths of all vibrational transitions from the ground state of a chiral molecule is zero.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] In July 1964, David Buckingham sailed from Southampton to Montréal, to take up a research post in Ottawa.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] On the voyage he met Jillian Bowles, a physiotherapist who was heading to a post in British Columbia.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] They were engaged in January 1965 and married at Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford six months later.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] They were married for over 55 years, and had three children: Lucy Elliot and Mark Vincent, born in Bristol, and Alice Susan born in Cambridge.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] Between them they had eight grandchildren: Carola, Peter, Oliver, William, Patrick, Anna, Samuel and Maeve.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-david-buckingham] David Buckingham died in Cambridge on 4 February 2021, seven days after his 91st birthday; he was survived by Jill, their children and grandchildren.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-r-davis-memorial-lecture] Davis Memorial Lecture** is held annually in commemoration of A.R.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-r-davis-memorial-lecture] Davis, the Professor of Oriental Studies at the University of Sydney and a key figure in post-war Asian Studies in Australia.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/a-r-davis-memorial-lecture] It is organised by the Australian Society for Asian Humanities (formerly the Oriental Society of Australia) and published in the *Journal of the Society for Asian Humanities* (formerly the *Journal of the Oriental Society of Australia*).
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert attended primary schools in Randwick and Coogee, but soon settled into the Scots College in Sydney where he excelled in both music and science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He was expected to join the family music-publishing business and while he maintained a lifelong love of music, he was more drawn towards the sciences.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] At first, a compromise was reached and he studied pharmacy part-time at the University of Sydney.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] However he did not enjoy the work and upon becoming a registered pharmacist in 1928, he left the profession to pursue his love of science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He was awarded BSc with first class honours and the University Medal in 1932 at the University of Sydney.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He gained a PhD in 1937 and a DSc in 1947 from the University of London.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] In 1939 he was a foundation member of the Drugs sub-committee of the Australian Association of Scientific Workers.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Despite his prolific research output and excellent reputation as a lecturer, in 1970 the university closed the Department of Medical Chemistry and spun its activities into the Medical Chemistry Group with a more limited scope.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert was a scholar of heterocyclic chemistry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He authored *Selective Toxicity: The Physico-Chemical Basis of Therapy*, first published by Chapman & Hall in 1951.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] In 1960, he founded the field of economic toxicology, which is the study of the harmful effects of chemicals which are intentionally administered by humans in order to achieve a result, such as pesticides.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert was known for his molecular approach to chemical pharmacology, which was more accepted in the USA compared to Europe at that time.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert travelled extensively and acted as a sort of roving ambassador for Australian science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert devoted his life to research: he did not like administrative work, and he only made himself available for lectures in the beginning and end parts of his academic career.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert was made an Officer of the Order of Australia (AO) in the 1989 Australia Day Honours for "services to medical chemistry, particularly in the fields of teaching and research".
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He was a Fellow of the Australian Academy of Science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] The Adrien Albert Laboratory of Medicinal Chemistry at the University of Sydney was established in his honour in 1989.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] His bequest funds the Adrien Albert Lectureship, awarded every two years by the Royal Society of Chemistry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] The Royal Australian Chemical Institute established the Adrien Albert award (Archived 19 February 2017 at the Wayback Machine) in his honour.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert was born to Jacques Albert, a businessman in the music industry, and his third wife, Mary Eliza Blanche Allen.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Albert had two much older half brothers, stemming from his father's previous marriage.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] After a few years, Jacques died, and so, Adrien Albert was raised by his mother and another relative.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Being tall and thin, Albert acquired the nickname "the snake" from his colleagues.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] It has been suggested that Albert suffered from Marfan syndrome however he was never diagnosed.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Overwork and poor diet during his PhD studies in London in the mid-1930s caused a stomach ulcer to haemmorage, requiring emergency surgery.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] The surgery saved his life however he suffered lifelong stomach complaints as a result.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Due to this ailment, he slept in every morning, but made up for time lost by working well into the night.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He never married, explaining that having a family would take time away from his research.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Other facets of his personality point towards a certain antipathy towards women: he drew cartoons for his friends about the dog Woofred and his wife, Ima Bitch, and he generally steered clear of female colleagues.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Ironically, given his lifetime of drug research and introduction of the term selective toxicity into medical chemistry, he died of complications arising from a long-running infection of drug-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] Fluent in French, German and Italian, Albert loved music and could play the piano very well, although he ceased to do so later in life.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/adrien-albert] He enjoyed botany, particularly exotic flowers and had an extensive knowledge of native Australian plants.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] Sargeson was born at Armidale, New South Wales, Australia.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] He was educated at the University of Sydney and received his Ph.D. supervised by Francis Patrick Dwyer also at Sydney in 1956.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] His first academic appointment was at the University of Adelaide and then in 1958 he rejoined Dwyer at the Australian National University.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] Sargeson was best known as a coordination chemist with an interest in bioinorganic chemistry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] In early work with Dwyer and throughout his career, he studied stereochemistry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] His research group investigated the reactions of amine ligands, culminating in the synthesis of the clathrochelates called "sepulchrates".
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 1983 and of the Australian Academy of Science in 1976.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alan-sargeson] Also in 1976, he became a foreign member of the Royal Danish Academy of Science and a corresponding member of the U.S.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Albert Ernest Alexander was born on 5 January 1914 in Ringwood, Hampshire, the sixth of seven children of William Albert Alexander, a master builder, and Beatrice (née Daw), formerly a teacher.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] He attended Brockenhurst County School, from where he gained a place in 1931 at the University of Reading.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] He graduated in 1934 with First Class Honours in Chemistry and an Open Scholarship to King's College, Cambridge.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] He was awarded a First Class in the Tripos Examination.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] With the benefit of a King's College Senior Scholarship, a DSIR grant for research, and a Ramsay Memorial Fellowship, Alexander joined the Department of Colloid Science to work under Professor E K Rideal (later Sir Eric Keightley Rideal, MBE, FRS).
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] He began with work on the orientation in films of long-chain esters and continued by examining porphyrins, chlorophylls and other molecules, with and without metals.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Alexander was awarded his PhD in 1938, and then went hitch-hiking in Scandinavia with his friend from Cambridge F S Dainton.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] During their holiday they visited Theodor Svedberg's laboratory in Uppsala in August 1938, after which Alexander decided he would like to spend as much time as he could working with Torsten Teorell in Uppsala.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] He started at the Institute of Medical Chemistry in December 1938, but had to return to England at the outbreak of war in September 1939.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] His work in that nine-month period was published that year.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] He returned to Cambridge, where he was elected a Fellow of King's College.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] In the Department of Colloid Science work continued on a wide range of topics including the role of hydrogen bonding in condensed monomolecular films and the effects of soaps and synthetic wetting agents on the biological activities of phenols.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Fourteen publications appeared in the war years.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] In 1944 Alexander became one of two Assistant Directors of Research in the Colloid Science Department; Gordon Sutherland was the other.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] On 6 February 1947 he delivered the Tilden Lecture in recognition of the prize he had been awarded by the Chemical Society of London.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] In October 1947 the Société de Chimie Physique and the Faraday Society held a joint discussion meeting at Bordeaux on Surface Chemistry, at which Alexander and colleagues gave five papers.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] In 1949 Alexander and Johnson published Colloid Science which an anonymous reviewer praised as a broad, modern, and authoritative treatment of the subject of colloid physics and chemistry from the fundamental rather than from the phenomenological viewpoint.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] In Australia, the government of New South Wales created an Institute of Technology as part of its plan to expand its technical education system at the tertiary level.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] They advertised for applications for a Chair in Applied Chemistry, to which Alexander was appointed.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] On 1 October 1949 he and his family sailed from London to Sydney on the RMS *Maloja*.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] They lived at 178 Raglan Street, Mosman, a suburb of Sydney, and only a short drive from the Sydney Technical College.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] During Alexander's seven years there he authored or co-authored some 40 papers.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Many involved systems of practical importance, such as efforts to reduce evaporation from dams, and the cattle tick problem in NSW.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] But, disillusioned with the lack of progress with the status of the Technical College to an autonomous university, Alexander moved to the University of Sydney in 1956.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Work was quickly restarted on topics that may be catalogued under four headings: (a) monolayer studies, (b) micellar solutions, (c) the roles of surfactants in heterogeneous polymerisations, and (d) the effects of polyelectrolytes on the crystallisations of sparingly soluble salts.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Fifty or more papers appeared from Alexander and his group.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Their work is described in detail in Le Fèvre’s memoir.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Albert married Catherine Robson in Cambridge in 1940.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] They had two children: Naomi, born in 1944 and a son, William Neil, known as Neil.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Naomi was killed in a car crash in the USA in 1966.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Catherine died of cancer 14 November 1963.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Two years later, on 10 December 1965 Alexander married Gisela Gudrum Baker (née Zutavern, of Heidelberg), the widow of Kingsley Ferguson Baker, a Sydney industrial chemist, at the Presbyterian Church in Pymble.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] Stricken by a brain tumour in 1969 when serving as dean of science, he died at his Mosman home on 23 May 1970 and was cremated.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] His wife, and the son of his first marriage, survived him.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/albert-ernest-alexander] The Pymble Church “was packed by friends, colleagues, and students on 26 May for a funeral service during which a moving panegyric was spoken by Professor I.G.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Alexander Boden was born on 28 May 1913, shortly after his parents William and Helena Boden arrived in Australia from Ireland.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] His parents established a drapery business in the main shopping centre of the Sydney suburb of Chatswood.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Alex was the middle child between his two sisters.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] His father, William Boden, was born in Ballinasloe on the border of counties Galway and Roscommon.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] In Williams youth, he went to join his uncle in the latter's evidently prosperous drapery story in Magherafelt, County Londonderry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] A surviving photograph of the staff of the store is impressive: some fifty men and women in starched collars and prim blouses stand in well-ordered ranks.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] The move to Australia in 1913 followed the emigration of William's two brothers and a sister.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] His mother, formerly Helena Isabella Hutchinson, a schoolteacher, came from Knockboy, near Broughshane, County Antrim, of a family of schoolteachers and clerics.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Alex Boden's education was at Willoughby Public School and North Sydney Boys High School.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] His father's premises were owned by the pharmacists Washington H.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Soul, Pattinson and Co. and one day, while the young Alex was still at school, his father asked his landlord what was the best career for a boy.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] In a greatly expanded sense it could be said that Alex Boden followed this advice.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] In 1929 Alex passed the Leaving Certificate with honours in Mathematics and Chemistry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] An exhibition took him to the University of Sydney, where he enrolled in science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] He was drawn to this area due to chemical experiments he undertook while at school.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] The last sentence revealing the hallmark of his life – self-reliance.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] He became a highly qualified Boy Scout leader.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] He spoke at the Sydney University Union's parliamentary-style Union Night debates and engaged in hockey and wrestling.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Alex recorded in his notebooks with carefully marshalled tables of the books he had read and his opinions of them.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] In his first university year, he records reading, wholly or in part, about a hundred books.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Representative entries from that year include *Better Ballroom Dancing* by Scott (75% read) with a note 'Correction of mistakes etc.'; *Goodbye to All That* by Robert Graves (all read) 'Good realistic.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] No censoring of language'; *Handbook of Photography* by Sinclair (most read) 'Pretty good but a bit old-fashioned'; *Religion and Science* by Draper (all read) 'V. readable'; *English Regal Copper Coins*, by Bamah (most read); 'Coins 16721860.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] No pics. may be good for reference'; *La Vie des Abeilles* by Maeterlinck (2/3 read) 'V.g.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Interesting and novel'; *Communist Manifesto* by Marx and Engels (all read) 'Quite fair.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Alex continued, with unabated assiduity and eclecticism, right through to the end of his fourth year – 400 titles, all similarly noted.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] He graduated with honours in the year 1933.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] While this account must shortly take up his business career, it will be convenient here to carry on with one of his subsequent extra-professional interests – the theatre.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] He joined The Playmakers and in 1934 made his debut in Crime Made Legal.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Advance publicity noted that 'Alex Boden is a newcomer to the Society and is making his first appearance in the important part of Inspector Burke.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] His fine speaking voice and confident bearing are sure to find favour.' It must be assumed that they did, for he made at least a dozen subsequent appearances, mostly with Sydney's oldest repertory company, The Sydney Players.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] His notices were generally flattering, as in A Midsummer Night's Dream: 'As Theseus, Alex Boden was easily the most competent of last night's performers.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] After 1936, however, the store of programmes and press clippings stops.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Aged twenty-four and watching now the last grains of 1937 run through our fingers.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] A book [his Handbook of Chemistry] was born in January.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Finances are dull but they have been smoothed sufficiently to give a little takeoff for 1938.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/alexander-boden] Sentiments not entirely controlled and showing no practical advance.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The **School of Chemistry, University of Sydney** is a school of the Faculty of Science at the University of Sydney.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The School of Chemistry was established as a part of the Faculty of Science in 1882.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] However, chemistry was taught at the University of Sydney since 1852.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] A purpose-built building was constructed on what was later named Science Road starting in 1888 and was completed in 1890.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The building was designed largely by Archibald Liversidge, Professor of Chemistry and the first Dean of the Faculty of Science.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The original Chemistry Building is now used by the Sydney Pharmacy School.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] In 1945, a large fibro-cement building (known as "Tramsheds") was constructed for use by chemistry students until the current Chemistry Building opened in 1958.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The current Chemistry Building is notable in architectural history as one of the first structures in Australia with a curtain wall design.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The School of Chemistry is home to the Laboratory of Advanced Catalysis for Sustainability which is focused broadly on catalysis, sustainable processes and fuels, green chemistry, and organometallic chemistry.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Other areas the group is interested in include batteries, nanoparticles, ionic liquids, biofuels, and nanostructured materials.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The School of Chemistry has a node of the Centre of Excellence in Exciton Science which is a research collaboration between the University of Melbourne, University of New South Wales, RMIT University, University of Sydney, and Monash University.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The Centre of Excellence in Exciton Science is focused on novel materials for the development of low-cost, high efficiency, light-harvesting devices.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The research programme utilises high-throughput screening, single molecule photochemistry, and ultrafast spectroscopy.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The Drug Discovery Initiative (DDI) was launched in 2018 to develop new drugs by working with clinicians and industry in infectious diseases, cancer, inflammation, neurodegenerative disorders, and metabolic diseases.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] However, the DDI is not limited to these areas and its research has contributed to antibiotics, cardiovascular diseases, and other health issues.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Much of the research of the DDI uses facilities made available by Sydney Analytical such as X-ray scattering techniques and various types of spectroscopy, usually for characterisation of new drugs or proteins.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Recent research within the DDI include Alzheimer's disease, malaria, and tuberculosis.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The current Academic Director of the DDI is Prof.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The Key Centre for Polymers and Colloids (KCPC) is a research centre of the School of Chemistry established by the Australian Research Council Research Centres Program.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] While the KCPC is known for polymers and colloids, it comprises several groups that can specialise in different areas like self-assembly, virus mimics, emulsions, and surfactants.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The KCPC has attracted various industry support such as Orica, Nuplex Industries, and others.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Currently, faculty members involved in KCPC research are: A/Prof.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Admission to the School of Chemistry's research programs is competitive.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Generally, admission to the School of Chemistry Honours program requires a SCIWAM of at least 65 or equivalent.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Each faculty member is limited to 2.5 full-time equivalent (FTE) Honours students to ensure adequate supervision where co-supervised projects count as 0.5 FTE for each faculty.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] As a result, admission for some projects is significantly more competitive than others.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The School of Chemistry offer postgraduate research degrees in the Doctor of Philosophy, Master of Philosophy, and Graduate Diploma in Science where admission is by application to the University of Sydney.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] Applications for funding and scholarships is a separate application but also to the University of Sydney, this is a competitive process and a successful candidate is typically offered a stipend and a scholarship to cover living expenses and tuition fees, respectively.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The University of Sydney has typically performed well on the QS Chemistry Subject Ranking, where it was 30th in 2013, 42nd in 2014, 51-100th in 2015, 49th in 2016, 50th in 2017, 43rd in 2018, and 51-100th in 2019.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] The University of Sydney has been 151-200th in the Academic Ranking of World Universities in chemistry since its inception in 2017.
[src:university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry/university-of-sydney-school-of-chemistry] News & World Report* ranked the School of Chemistry, University of Sydney 138th in the world and 6th in Australia.
